## ScamBuster- Stop Scams in Real time
James Riedel, Spring 2026



#### Abstract:    

In the digital age that we live in, scams and digital fraud are becoming more and more prevalent every single day. Whether it’s via social media, over the phone, email, or text, scams are everywhere and are constantly evolving. Because of this, individuals often lack awareness and education regarding these scams therefore falling victim to them, resulting in financial loss, hardship, and emotional distress. This paper goes in depth on the project management scope and outline of ScamBuster, an open-source, community operated scam prevention system and network to combat these digital crimes. This system allows scams to be reported, documented, and publicized in real time to avoid having to rely on publications and law enforcement which is often too slow for the ever changing scam environment. Based on various project management concepts from the course, the network focuses on community engagement, workflow development, roadmaps, and more to accurately, urgently, and efficiently educate and update the community on digital scams.

#### Background:

In the society that we live in, technology and online services are apparent in most tasks in our everyday lives. While these services seem to make our lives more efficient and convenient, it comes with a cost; the risk of being scammed and taken advantage of. Every single online service opens their users up with this risk whether it is a simple social media site, or a banking application. Scammers usually either prey on vulnerable individuals using a fake persona or pretending to be a legitimate business, and then convince the individuals to send them money using various methods such as: crypto atm deposits, gift cards, wire transfers, Paypal/Venmo/Cashapp, and in some extreme circumstances, physical in person money mules. While anyone can fall victim to scams, the primary target for them are the elderly due to often lack of technological proficiency. (FBI, 2026)
Every single day, vulnerable individuals fall victim to these scams, often losing thousands, if not their entire life savings causing extreme distress and financial hardship. Lives get ruined daily over this. This happens due to many factors. First, with the constant enhancements of technology, such as AI, users have trouble staying proficient with it therefore are more prone to not be able to distinguish what to believe. In addition, there are very few sources for scam information and typically when there is, it is from a major publication site to where the scammer would have already been made aware of the exposure and most-likely already changed the scam so it is too late. Lastly, most scams originate outside of the United States therefore law enforcement don’t typically get involved or attempt to prevent and stop these scams which makes them much more common. This is a major problem which can be very mitigated and prevented with education and awareness.

#### Project Overview:

ScamBuster is a free, open source system and network that aims to help prevent and mitigate scams using direct community involvement and engagement. Users report their scam experience providing as much information and evidence as they can. It will then be uploaded and sent to a database where community members verify the legitimacy of the scam and if it is still active using various methods such as scambaiting (fake baiting the scammer to learn more information on the scam), call bots, and victim testimonials. Once verified, the report will then be flagged into a certain category based on factors such as risk level which users are able to view on the site. Users will additionally have the ability to mark notes into the report that they come across such as call recordings, scammer names, triggers to upset the scammers, etc. If the report is later flagged as inactive by someone, the scam report will return to an unverified status and require reverification to maintain legitimacy and remove scams that are no longer active. This way, users can stay informed of active scams, report new ones, and help make a safer community. In addition, there will be forums available to discuss various scam resources, insights, testimonials, etc. The network doesn’t aim to be associated with or mimic law enforcement; but more so to educate the public.

#### Project Scope/First Steps:

Early on, it may be difficult to implement a community driven network due to the lack of users to verify and act on various things. To combat this, the network will initially develop a bare-bones minimalistic version of the service that does an incredibly basic iteration of the main objective. This will be a simple site with 2 pages: the reporting form, and the reports page, both being very simplistic and bare. This is primarily in order to break the project into smaller tasks that can be added on later on. With this iteration, we can start establishing a community, as well as make sure that the things that are most important are being considered, which is giving the users access to the reports to be aware of them. Any form of verification is not established yet due to the lack of initial community where many reports would likely go unnoticed therefore remain unverified. Even if they could get verified, it would be from one person which would question the credibility of the site. Also forums and user interaction is intentionally not implemented yet also due to the lack of community.

#### Workflow:

In order to layout and organize the overall flow of the network, a workflow is needed. First, the user submits the scam which is available to do so on the home page. On the page, there will be many questions such as dates, times, type of scam, how the user came across it, any evidence, etc. At this point the user will get a confirmation email notifying them that they successfully reported a scam. The report then appears on the reports page, under the unverified tab. Users will be able to add any information they have on the specific scam as well as contribute legitimacy using the verify icon where the user can select if they discovered that the scam is still active or is shut down. One verification may not flag the report as verified; however if users have accurately verified many reports in the past, their verification is more impactful with the official status than other accounts as well as many verifications would result in the report being formally moved to the verified status. Once a report is verified, it is moved to the re-verification tab if someone marks it as no longer active which if more people flag it as such it will be removed. If the report is removed, it is moved to the legacy report tab where users can see all the past reports to make connections and potentially find patterns in scams and where they are coming from. This way, users are constantly up to date on various scams, are verified on legitimacy, and removed if outdated.

