#### Community Model:

The network is completely dependent on open community engagement and participation. There will be 4 roles users can earn, all based on merit such as accurate verifications, active engagement, positive behavior, etc. There will be various metrics that track these roles and they can be added or removed as well as users can have multiple roles. The first role is Learner. Learner is the most basic role and is automatically given to anyone who creates an account. Learners have access to make a report, view other reports, and verify them, however their influence to change statuses is very low, and would require many learners to change it. The next role is reporter. This is given when a user reports 5 different scams and are all verified. When they make a report, it gets moved more towards the top of reports and gets prioritized for verification. The third role is verifier. This is given when the user has accurately verified 5 different reports which all ended up being officially verified by user consensus. These users have a much higher influence in officially changing the statuses on unverified reports and need very few others to do so. The final role is moderator. This is given out on a case by case basis to individuals who show loyalty and merit and is chosen by the owner. Moderators have everything that the other roles have but also have the ability to moderate the forum, enforce rules, ban/mute someone, etc. They keep the network a safe and powerful resource.

#### Governance and Moderation:

Since the network is fully community based, it makes sense that all decisions are made public and influenced by the community as well. Full transparency is the main objective when it comes to governance in the network to allow the community to establish trust, confidence, and eagerness to participate. This is done by releasing frequent update logs, newsletters, and “town hall” meetings. 
In addition, like any public service, there are likely to be bots, spam, abuse, trolling, and even scams on the anti-scam site. To combat this, there needs to be a moderation system. Before moderation can be implemented, there needs to be a terms of service and code of conduct which states what would be allowed and not allowed while engaging with the site. In the site, there will be a report button next to every report and forum post. When pressed, the reporter will select what infraction the post violates and it will be submitted where moderators are notified and have access to it. Moderators then will determine if it does violate the guidelines to determine whether the post will be removed or not. In an instance of repeated offenses, accounts may be banned or even IP banned. This way all users can help keep the site safe which also encourages engagement and participation. This allows community moderation without giving users total control to maintain stability.

#### Technical Debt:

Technical debt is apparent in every project. In this particular instance, scams are forever changing and evolving. Because of this, there will be many things that would help the project accumulate technical debt over time. First, the specific platforms and ways users use the internet is also constantly changing therefore if the infrastructure and input options of the network is set up for one period of the internet, it may not allow the user to report things accurately later on due to lack of options or variety when reporting. For example, if current social media platforms are currently flooded with scams and the site is prepared for only those current scams to be displayed, if a newer social media came out that requires a whole different format to accurately report the scam, it may not allow the user to do so to the fullest potential resulting in scams going unreported. To combat this, the reporting format and overall layout of the reporting aspect needs to be incredibly versatile and universally formatted to accommodate every type of scam there is.
Another factor of technical debt is the project revolving around building a community rather than the stability of the site itself. The network can only function if the community exists and due to that it needs to constantly grow. As more users join and the site becomes more populated, some policies and algorithms may not be as beneficial and accurate as they used to be. For example, in early stages, one verifier may be able to change the status of a report but if that happens when there are hundreds of verifiers that exist, it can be abused very quickly to provide misinformation. To combat this, algorithms need to be percentage and majority based instead of set numbers.

#### Sustainability:

There are many factors that allow the network to sustain in the long term and continue to grow. First, the user base needs to constantly sign up more users as well as retaining existing users. In order to do this, there needs to be marketing or awareness of the network. This can be done using various methods, such as partnering with scam related organizations such as scambait Youtube channels or remote control software such as Anydesk (their software is often a tool used by scammers). Not only would this bring more users, it would also potentially bring revenue to the network. 
Revenue is also crucial to the survival and sustainability of the site. Without revenue, the servers, third party software, equipment and other costs cannot be paid. In addition to business partnerships, ads can be run on the site. The additional profit that is made can also be given to the users as an incentive to report scams therefore retaining the existing users. Donations can also be an option and can be elevated using scam awareness campaigns which bring in revenue but also spreads awareness and makes the site more well known.

#### Conclusion:

In conclusion, scams are always prevalent in society and are part of every online service. Victims constantly fall victim to scams and the effects can be catastrophic. ScamBuster allows scams to be identified and publicized in real time in order to educate the public before it’s too late and therefore protect the community making society an overall safer place. Its community driven infrastructure means that the network is created for the people, by the people so it is exactly what they want and benefits to the most potential. This open source project makes scam victims and those who are sick of scammers have a voice which they could never have before.

